00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:16.779
The phone company knows that my phone's here
and your phone's there.

00:12:16.779 --> 00:12:20.670
If they can tell your phone to go left and
mine to go right, there's no traffic.

00:12:20.670 --> 00:12:21.670
That was the insight.

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:24.100
And a lot of people go, "Well, you're talking
about tech stuff.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:25.420
I'm not an engineer."

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:29.870
How many lines of code did Steve Jobs write
in his career building the world's biggest

00:12:29.870 --> 00:12:30.870
tech company?

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:31.870
Tom Bilyeu: Zero.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:32.870
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:33.870
So we all live with technology.

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:37.139
But you bring up a bigger point.

00:12:37.139 --> 00:12:41.230
What's driving me right now?

00:12:41.230 --> 00:12:45.439
Our world is changing at a pace that most
people can't grasp.

00:12:45.439 --> 00:12:48.569
Government's definitely can't grasp it right
now.

00:12:48.569 --> 00:12:55.029
That is if we go back 100 years ago, half
the people worked on farms, and half the people

00:12:55.029 --> 00:12:56.029
worked in cities.

00:12:56.029 --> 00:12:59.310
And two pieces of technology: irrigation and
the tractor.

00:12:59.310 --> 00:13:04.950
Today, we have 2% of the people making food
for all of the US and exporting.

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:09.149
That means half the people lost their jobs
on farms, but they were absorbed by the Industrial

00:13:09.149 --> 00:13:10.199
Revolution.

00:13:10.199 --> 00:13:15.180
So we live during a century where we saw a
half of the jobs disappear.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:19.839
Now we're living in a time where over the
next 10 years, half of all jobs will disappear.

00:13:19.839 --> 00:13:21.980
Robotics replacing unskilled labor.

00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:26.600
You raise minimum wage to assemble a burger,
a robot will assemble a burger, a robot will

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:27.600
make a pizza.

00:13:27.600 --> 00:13:31.089
An app will take your order.

00:13:31.089 --> 00:13:35.910
White collar jobs, half of middle management
jobs over the next five years are going to

00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:36.910
disappear.

00:13:36.910 --> 00:13:39.529
Number one job on tax returns is truck driver.

00:13:39.529 --> 00:13:42.680
Eight percent of the population drives a vehicle.

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:44.290
Autonomous vehicles, those are gone.

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:45.290
Autonomous boats.

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:46.290
Everything.

00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:48.100
3D printing, et cetera, et cetera.

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:53.689
So even your professionals, AI systems and
machine learning get rid of a lot of lawyers,

00:13:53.689 --> 00:13:56.910
a lot of doctors, a lot of accounting.

00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:58.970
What do you do with all those people?

00:13:58.970 --> 00:14:02.600
What makes life enjoyable is a stable middle
class.

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:05.470
So no bullshit, how do you solve that?

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:08.470
How do you build a big middle class?

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:12.839
The same technology that is automating away
those things that were mundane and don't need

00:14:12.839 --> 00:14:17.360
to be repeated connects us to billions of
other people.

00:14:17.360 --> 00:14:21.290
So you can now solve problems that scale much
quicker.

00:14:21.290 --> 00:14:28.139
From 2008 in the recession, all of the job
gains globally have come from entrepreneurs.

00:14:28.139 --> 00:14:30.389
They haven't come from big business.

00:14:30.389 --> 00:14:33.560
So how do you teach people to start companies?

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:36.459
How do you get people to replicate your journey?

00:14:36.459 --> 00:14:38.790
It can be in almost any field.

00:14:38.790 --> 00:14:42.560
If you have a life with no problems, yeah,
there's nothing to do.

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:46.130
Tom Bilyeu: Let me ask you a question that's
going to draw a line for people.

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:49.560
Do you plan to monetize that or is this purely
philanthropic for you?

00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:53.889
Jay Samit: The goal isn't for me to monetize.

00:14:53.889 --> 00:14:57.850
I've been very lucky, and life's good, and
the kids are good.

00:14:57.850 --> 00:14:59.740
I didn't write the book to make money.

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:07.290
I did it to scale ... I was teaching how to
build a high tech startup.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:08.290
I taught.

00:15:08.290 --> 00:15:12.120
The most successful was two students did $150
million in top line their first year.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:13.170
Tom Bilyeu: Good lord.

00:15:13.170 --> 00:15:14.170
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:15:14.170 --> 00:15:15.209
Makes you really feel like a failure.

00:15:15.209 --> 00:15:16.209
Brilliant idea.

00:15:16.209 --> 00:15:18.720
One of the best pitches I've ever heard.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:24.040
I judge hackathons around the world, and I'm
turning the hackathon experience into a TV

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:29.410
show to teach people how to do this because
let's go from the selfish standpoint.

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:35.610
If all an entrepreneur does is solve problems,
who are they solving them for?

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:36.839
Everybody else.

00:15:36.839 --> 00:15:40.180
I have problems, I would like a better world.

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:45.000
So the more people that are solving problems,
the better life is for everybody.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:50.050
We were taught that there was like only so
many slices of pie, and it's mine or yours,

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:52.560
a zero sum game.

00:15:52.560 --> 00:15:54.439
That isn't how the world really works.

00:15:54.439 --> 00:15:57.189
That isn't how capital is created.

00:15:57.189 --> 00:16:01.430
You create a new company, and somebody buys
stock for $10, and somebody else buys stock

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:06.060
for 20, you've now created a whole bunch of
money that didn't exist in the system.

00:16:06.060 --> 00:16:09.019
People don't realize money isn't all printed
by a government.

00:16:09.019 --> 00:16:11.149
Entrepreneurs actually create money.

00:16:11.149 --> 00:16:18.639
Bitcoin created a new currency that may end
up being more trustworthy than any nation-state

00:16:18.639 --> 00:16:20.009
currency.

00:16:20.009 --> 00:16:26.449
It's an amazing time to be on the planet,
so if I can help people achieve that success

00:16:26.449 --> 00:16:29.250
... Take it on the simplest.

00:16:29.250 --> 00:16:33.389
We'd love going to a movie that cost $200
million to make, back to the Star Wars thing.

00:16:33.389 --> 00:16:37.459
I love living in a world where somebody's
willing to spend $200 million to entertain

00:16:37.459 --> 00:16:39.410
my ass for two hours.

00:16:39.410 --> 00:16:40.699
It doesn't get better than that.

00:16:40.699 --> 00:16:44.959
Tom Bilyeu: The reason I ask you about the
path to monetization is I think one of the

00:16:44.959 --> 00:16:48.199
things ... It's the middle ground that people
get lost in.

00:16:48.199 --> 00:16:53.070
You can show people that, hey, I used to be,
what I say, I used to have a slave mentality.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:56.459
I kept my head down, did as little work as
possible, and avoided punishment at all costs.

00:16:56.459 --> 00:16:59.139
Then I can show you that I was very, very
successful.

00:16:59.139 --> 00:17:01.819
But people don't get to see that in-between.

00:17:01.819 --> 00:17:06.309
And what I think you're doing just amazingly
well, and what people will get in the book,

00:17:06.309 --> 00:17:09.110
are literally the things that you have to
do to your mind, the ways you have to think,

00:17:09.110 --> 00:17:14.760
the sort of baseline belief systems you have
to bring on to your own life that are going

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:18.790
to allow you go take this grand idea ... If
I want to build a massive middle class, maybe

00:17:18.790 --> 00:17:22.330
you're not thinking of that particular problem
this way, but you can take whatever your grand

00:17:22.330 --> 00:17:29.350
problem is, and then how do I create an ecosystem
around it that's financially self-sustaining?

00:17:29.350 --> 00:17:34.910
And allowing people the things that they need
to do to their mind to create a real business.

00:17:34.910 --> 00:17:39.810
Jay Samit: When you read Disrupt You, I'm
putting you on the spot, was there anything

00:17:39.810 --> 00:17:43.890
that I said or laid out in those chapters
that after the light bulb went out and you

00:17:43.890 --> 00:17:48.340
go, "Wow, I never saw I that way" that you
didn't instantly absorb and say "Oh, yeah,

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:49.610
this makes sense"?

00:17:49.610 --> 00:17:52.570
Tom Bilyeu: I kind of know what you're asking.

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:57.400
Yes, there were things that were watershed
moments for me, which is why I think the book

00:17:57.400 --> 00:17:58.400
is so important.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:00.310
But they were in hindsight, self evident.

00:18:00.310 --> 00:18:01.940
Jay Samit: That's the point.

00:18:01.940 --> 00:18:05.830
None of this stuff is not common sense.

00:18:05.830 --> 00:18:11.220
It's just we were pushed down a path of blinders
our whole lives.

00:18:11.220 --> 00:18:13.810
For well-intentioned reasons in many cases.

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:18.520
But the educational system was designed to
have you work at a factory.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:24.590
The IQ test was invented to let the Army know
which people were cannon fodder, and you could

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:27.710
just let them get killed, and which people
had potential.

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:31.680
When in fact, we all have potential.

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:36.520
What we have to do is figure out where to
channel it and what are those steps.

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:39.290
There's no gatekeepers to capital anymore.

00:18:39.290 --> 00:18:44.900
There's no exclusive country club or college
or this or that.

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:49.260
And we're all interconnected, so it doesn't
matter whether you're in a big city or in

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:53.250
Botswana, you can still reach six billion
consumers.

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:57.080
So what's stopping you?

00:18:57.080 --> 00:18:59.430
That fear of failure.

00:18:59.430 --> 00:19:02.720
That "Oh, if I fail what will people say?"

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:04.210
Failing's a great thing.

00:19:04.210 --> 00:19:06.520
Failing teaches you what doesn't work.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:10.030
Failure is throwing in the towel.

00:19:10.030 --> 00:19:15.620
You take that job to be secure, you go for
that big Fortune 500 company, and most of

00:19:15.620 --> 00:19:19.040
the Fortune 500 companies go out of business.

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:21.420
There's less than 10% of them left.

00:19:21.420 --> 00:19:22.420
That's amazing statement.

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:23.420
Of the original list.

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:24.420
Tom Bilyeu: Yeah.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:25.420
No kidding.

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:27.830
Jay Samit: So it's not the security that's
robbing ambition, it's the illusion of security

00:19:27.830 --> 00:19:29.500
that robs ambition.

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:33.130
So the biggest risk you can take in life is
not taking one.

00:19:33.130 --> 00:19:36.180
If you're at that point where you're in the
middle of your career, and you lost your job,

00:19:36.180 --> 00:19:41.300
or you're just out of college and starting,
or just out of high school, go talk to a senior

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:45.920
citizen about what they really regret about
their lives.

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:47.240
It's not what they failed at.

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:49.890
It's what they didn't try.

00:19:49.890 --> 00:19:51.550
It's the regrets of "Why didn't I?"

00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:56.990
If you try something and you fail, you learn
a skill set for something else.

00:19:56.990 --> 00:20:03.750
Steve Jobs, a great entrepreneur, college
wasn't for him, he bounced around, but he

00:20:03.750 --> 00:20:06.340
audited and took a class in calligraphy.

00:20:06.340 --> 00:20:07.340
It's useless.

00:20:07.340 --> 00:20:08.830
What's the point of that?

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:13.200
But when it came the time of the birth of
the PC, and IBM had all the rational ways

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:17.470
to make a good machine, he remembered that
calligraphy course and said, "We're going

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:19.190
to have fonts on our machine."

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:24.130
One divergent of "We got a few fonts here,
and these guys only have one," graphic artists

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:25.850
are using this machine.

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:33.870
Adobe, the whole future music, the iPod, the
iPhone, all come from one calligraphy class.

00:20:33.870 --> 00:20:38.110
Tom Bilyeu: What's one of the most important
things you hope people take away from the

00:20:38.110 --> 00:20:39.110
book?

00:20:39.110 --> 00:20:46.210
Jay Samit: That all of the big famous people
that you hear about, Richard Branson and Steve

00:20:46.210 --> 00:20:52.970
Jobs and Zuckerberg and everyone, they're
no different than you are.

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:58.150
Seventy-something percent of the world's billionaires
are self-made.

00:20:58.150 --> 00:21:00.780
You can achieve this.

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:02.210
It's not going to be easy.

00:21:02.210 --> 00:21:06.050
You don't just wake up on Tuesday and become
rich on Wednesday.

00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:12.170
But it doesn't take any more effort than going
to a job that you hate.

00:21:12.170 --> 00:21:16.810
And unless you believe in reincarnation, you
got one shot on this planet.

00:21:16.810 --> 00:21:18.560
One shot.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:21.870
So don't you want to make a difference?

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:27.640
Don't you want to leave something behind and
make the planet better than you found it?

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:28.860
Why are you here?

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:30.860
What do you want to accomplish with your life?

00:21:30.860 --> 00:21:34.610
It doesn't have to be [inaudible 00:21:31],
and it doesn't have to be money-oriented.

00:21:34.610 --> 00:21:38.671
The same principles that disrupt you, you
can change the educational system, you can

00:21:38.671 --> 00:21:39.671
change healthcare.

00:21:39.671 --> 00:21:45.690
I am humbled by what I'm seeing people create
around the world with so little.

00:21:45.690 --> 00:21:49.820
But we are on this ball together.

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:51.920
We can solve problems together.

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:54.800
We can make a better future together.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:22:01.450
It's an optimistic story that you get to write
your piece of the story.

00:22:01.450 --> 00:22:05.710
Why wouldn't people want to push their potential?

00:22:05.710 --> 00:22:06.710
Aim for the stars.

00:22:06.710 --> 00:22:08.800
If you don't make it all the way, you made
it to the moon.

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:09.890
Not bad.

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:15.620
Tom Bilyeu: That notion of solving these problems
together, I think is exactly what I took away

00:22:15.620 --> 00:22:16.620
from the book.

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:19.880
Or at least problem solving in general, and
that's one of the things I think people, when

00:22:19.880 --> 00:22:22.610
they read the book, they're going to find
example after example that will light them

00:22:22.610 --> 00:22:23.610
on fire.

00:22:23.610 --> 00:22:24.610
I'll give you a few of my favorites.

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:29.020
I'd love some more color or how people can
get better at this.

00:22:29.020 --> 00:22:31.050
When you first start, you think "Oh, man.

00:22:31.050 --> 00:22:32.050
No brainer.

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:34.250
I've got this device that's for the lottery."

00:22:34.250 --> 00:22:35.250
Right?

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:36.250
Jay Samit: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:22:36.250 --> 00:22:37.250
Tom Bilyeu: So you've got the old school lottery
thing.

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:41.540
It's those ugly, sort of green, one color
dot matrix-y looking thing.

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:46.100
Then you had this display panel, this beautiful
... It could talk if I'm not mistaken.

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:47.100
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:50.330
Got to go back before we all had PCs, before
computers were everywhere.

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:54.120
I'm that old, yes.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:58.420
Lotteries were coming out to different states,
and they had a little thing with the little

00:22:58.420 --> 00:23:02.270
just green numbers that you type in, and then
it prints your ticket.

00:23:02.270 --> 00:23:05.770
There was a contract for California.

00:23:05.770 --> 00:23:10.240
We had a six-foot-tall machine, big color
screen, a motion detector.

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:11.570
Again, this is 1980s.

00:23:11.570 --> 00:23:13.380
You walk by in the supermarkets, "Psst.

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:15.610
What would you do with $1 million?"

00:23:15.610 --> 00:23:18.560
And you're looking around because nobody every
talked to you before.

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:21.960
This machine could should you the cars and
the yachts and all this stuff.

00:23:21.960 --> 00:23:22.960
And you could touch.

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:28.730
Oh, and by the way, it said "Touch me" in
six different languages, if I remember correctly.

00:23:28.730 --> 00:23:31.910
So if you only spoke Vietnamese, boom, now
the machine does it.

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:33.890
You could make your own things.

00:23:33.890 --> 00:23:36.770
And I'm now going to go for the biggest contract
in my life.

00:23:36.770 --> 00:23:39.700
I'm in my early 20s.

00:23:39.700 --> 00:23:43.020
Every penny I have is into this.

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:46.370
I'm up against a company that has this little
green thing.

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:49.340
I'm as cocky as can be.

00:23:49.340 --> 00:23:50.340
This is it.

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:55.510
I go to this meeting, I win the contract,
I'll be a millionaire, life is good, dah dah

00:23:55.510 --> 00:23:56.510
dah.

00:23:56.510 --> 00:23:59.950
Two fun things that maybe I didn't elaborate
in the book.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:02.500
Didn't get the contract.

00:24:02.500 --> 00:24:08.650
Turns out the FBI had a secret camera videoing
in a hotel room where somebody, a state Senator

00:24:08.650 --> 00:24:13.680
named Alan Robbins, took a suitcase of $50,000
to vote for the other guys.

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:18.130
Even though the FBI sent him to prison, and
that's all true and fact, they didn't invalidate

00:24:18.130 --> 00:24:20.540
the awarding of the contract to my competition.

00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:21.540
Tom Bilyeu: That's crazy.

00:24:21.540 --> 00:24:26.140
Jay Samit: Now I'm flying back to LA.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:30.600
I didn't know how to raise money for my first
company, so I had like 10 credit cards all

00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:31.600
maxed out.

00:24:31.600 --> 00:24:34.560
I can't pay them.

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:36.060
I don't know what I'm going to do.

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:39.700
I don't even have enough money to take a cab
home from LAX.

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:43.340
I'm trying to figure out the bus system in
Los Angeles.

00:24:43.340 --> 00:24:46.250
Public transportation, not our strong suit.

00:24:46.250 --> 00:24:51.140
They used to have, back in the '80s, these
nice counters manned by volunteer little old

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:55.360
ladies that would tell you how to get a bus
or a cab or a van or a hotel or anything.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:58.300
Of course, by the time I got back, there's
nobody there.

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:00.000
I go, "Wait a second.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:03.130
If she was there, she could only speak English.

00:25:03.130 --> 00:25:06.730
She would only know a certain amount of information.

00:25:06.730 --> 00:25:08.810
There's visitors from tons of languages.

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:10.901
Why don't you put a kiosk here?

00:25:10.901 --> 00:25:13.860
Why don't you let people get all the information
and have live data?"

00:25:13.860 --> 00:25:16.980
This is before the internet and before smartphones,
before any of that.

00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:21.980
Today, when you go through an airport, everything
you do is with a kiosk.

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:23.170
My back was against the wall.

00:25:23.170 --> 00:25:31.131
I didn't set out to do a kiosk there, and
most of my early successes were somebody else

00:25:31.131 --> 00:25:35.630
developed a piece of technology that didn't
hit its mark, and I'm going, "Oh, wow.

00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:40.490
They got $100 million into making those laser
discs, and nobody's buying them for their

00:25:40.490 --> 00:25:41.490
home.

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:42.490
They're interactive.

00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:43.490
That'd be good for corporate training.

00:25:43.490 --> 00:25:44.490
Let me go sell that to Ford.

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:47.010
Let me go sell that to this one and that one."

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:52.870
So I started realizing that it wasn't the
inventors of technology, it was the people

00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:55.120
that brought them to market.

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:56.940
I have the skill set to do that.

00:25:56.940 --> 00:26:01.980
I just have to figure out what something and
move it somewhere else.

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:07.640
That was the genesis of a whole life where
I suddenly look back one day and go, "Wow,

00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:09.320
I came how far?

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:10.320
Doing what?"

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:11.320
Tom Bilyeu: Yeah.

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:12.320
I had this sense.

00:26:12.320 --> 00:26:16.770
I'm reading the book, and I have this sense
that I started to envision myself walking

00:26:16.770 --> 00:26:21.600
through the world pushing piles of cash out
the way to like get to whatever stupid thing

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:23.010
it was that I was trying to do.

00:26:23.010 --> 00:26:27.970
Because every story you would tell would start
with, like that one, where it was abject failure.

00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:33.080
You're in the airport and now no longer have
enough money to get home, but from that comes

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:34.740
your first massive success.

00:26:34.740 --> 00:26:35.740
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:26:35.740 --> 00:26:40.390
Tom Bilyeu: Then there was another story where
you're doing music, you've got this whole

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:45.540
great idea for launching this new digital
service, nobody's going for it, and you come

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:48.290
up with the idea of the concert in the sky.

00:26:48.290 --> 00:26:50.650
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:52.260
Didn't come up with the idea for concert in
the sky.

00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:53.620
Back to failure.

00:26:53.620 --> 00:26:56.640
Richard Branson who's launched eight billion-dollar
companies.

00:26:56.640 --> 00:26:58.490
He's launched about 300 companies.

00:26:58.490 --> 00:27:04.860
The most genius thing that Richard ever did
in hindsight was his brand is Virgin, which

00:27:04.860 --> 00:27:08.170
means you're a newbie, you don't know what
you're doing.

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:12.610
So every company of his that fails only strengthens
the brand.

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:13.670
He's not afraid to try.

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:14.670
Virgin Cola.

00:27:14.670 --> 00:27:17.490
Oh, the other guys have every piece of distribution
on Earth?

00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:19.300
End of Virgin Cola.

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:25.830
Anyway, he had had this idea of doing for
Virgin Airlines, a concert in the sky, but

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.140
it's against FAA rules to play an instrument
on an airplane.

00:27:29.140 --> 00:27:30.140
Tom Bilyeu: Really?

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:31.140
Jay Samit: Yeah.

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:35.410
There used to be an airline called MGM that,
in the upstairs of the 747, had a piano bar,

00:27:35.410 --> 00:27:40.050
and the other people couldn't compete, so
they banned so that they can't play an instrument.

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:43.920
Because they could interfere with the electronics
and everything else.

00:27:43.920 --> 00:27:48.520
Anyway, I have to launch something up against
iTunes.

00:27:48.520 --> 00:27:49.960
I don't have the same budget.

00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:53.140
They're spending $100 million a year advertising.

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:56.030
So I go, "Okay, who's got problems?

00:27:56.030 --> 00:27:58.320
Let me look and see who's got problems."

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:01.070
There were two companies that had bad years.

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:06.700
United, one of the biggest carriers, was in
bankruptcy and was trying to come out of bankruptcy.

00:28:06.700 --> 00:28:10.900
And Spurlock had just done Super Size Me,
and McDonald's sales were down.

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:11.900
Great.

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:14.480
Now I've got my partners.

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:18.460
Now I just have to figure out how to make
what I want to do their priority and spend

00:28:18.460 --> 00:28:20.420
their money to launch my store.

00:28:20.420 --> 00:28:21.420
That's the way I think.

00:28:21.420 --> 00:28:22.420
Tom Bilyeu: That's brilliant.

00:28:22.420 --> 00:28:25.600
You've said that there's no such thing as
not having money or running out of money or

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:26.600
something like that.

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:27.600
Jay Samit: Right.

00:28:27.600 --> 00:28:28.600
OPM, other people's money.

00:28:28.600 --> 00:28:32.710
There's somebody else who wants to reach the
same audience that you do.

00:28:32.710 --> 00:28:34.860
Most likely, they don't have a new, fresh
idea.

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:38.090
If you bring a fresh idea, they already have
it budgeted.

00:28:38.090 --> 00:28:42.260
So for McDonald's we did a buy a Big Mac,
get a free track.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:46.980
A secret code on every Big Mac package, and
you get a free download from my store.

00:28:46.980 --> 00:28:51.280
But you have to register at my new store to
get it, so 20 million customers registered

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:52.280
the first week.

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:56.210
Because nobody does marketing, TV commercials,
in-store signage, and I held out on the contract

00:28:56.210 --> 00:29:01.080
for the tray liner, so when the kids are playing
in the Happy Meal Land, mom and dad are reading

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:05.110
every line of "Ooh, I can get free music."

00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:06.380
Amazing marketing partner.

00:29:06.380 --> 00:29:07.600
Amazing company.

00:29:07.600 --> 00:29:12.390
By the way, because I know you're into health
and nutrition, if America wanted to eat tofu,

00:29:12.390 --> 00:29:14.560
McDonald's would be the number one seller
of tofu.

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:17.590
They know marketing.

00:29:17.590 --> 00:29:19.190
Then I went to United and said, "Wow.

00:29:19.190 --> 00:29:22.170
You have all these people who used to fly
with you that have enough miles, it turned

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:25.820
out, to go back and forth to Pluto nine times.

00:29:25.820 --> 00:29:29.370
Let's let them use their frequent flyer miles
to get music in the store.

00:29:29.370 --> 00:29:32.210
And to announce this, we'll do this concert."

00:29:32.210 --> 00:29:35.690
So I took out of my back pocket somebody else's
idea that they didn't execute.

00:29:35.690 --> 00:29:38.830
Sheryl Crow, 30,000 feet.

00:29:38.830 --> 00:29:42.640
Then we filled the plane with nothing but
journalists.

00:29:42.640 --> 00:29:50.680
Shot a nine-camera shoot, edited it on Vaio
laptops in first class, so when they got off

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:54.230
the plane, they had an edited piece that could
lead the evening news.

00:29:54.230 --> 00:29:56.930
They painted the outside of the plane.

00:29:56.930 --> 00:29:59.570
This whole thing costs nothing.

00:29:59.570 --> 00:30:00.600
Not a penny.

00:30:00.600 --> 00:30:04.580
Tom Bilyeu: Didn't it actually earn you like
$3 million before it even started?

00:30:04.580 --> 00:30:05.580
Jay Samit: Yes.

00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:10.310
One of the punchlines of it was McDonald's
had done this great promotion for the Olympics

00:30:10.310 --> 00:30:16.340
that was in Los Angeles that every time the
US got a gold medal, you got a free french

00:30:16.340 --> 00:30:17.900
fries or free burger or something.

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:23.830
And Russia pulled out, so we won all the medals,
and McDonald's lost millions and millions

00:30:23.830 --> 00:30:24.830
of dollars with the promotion.

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:29.330
So they took out insurance on all their other
promotions in case freak things happen.

00:30:29.330 --> 00:30:34.150
What if everybody redeemed, and the price
of this music was outrageous.

00:30:34.150 --> 00:30:38.560
After I got this signed off to do this whole
thing, McDonald's says, "Okay, we have to

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:39.580
get insurance for this."

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:41.240
I go, "Oh, yeah."

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:45.030
Everything's printed, done, I've told everybody,
it's about to launch.

00:30:45.030 --> 00:30:47.530
"The insurance in six million dollars, so
you got to pitch in three."

00:30:47.530 --> 00:30:49.330
I don't have three million.

00:30:49.330 --> 00:30:55.660
I can't go to my boss and, "Oops, I made a
$3 million mistake."

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:57.010
That's called career ending.

00:30:57.010 --> 00:30:59.440
So I'm like, "I'm screwed.

00:30:59.440 --> 00:31:00.560
This is over."

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:02.970
I'm like, "I got into something I don't understand.

00:31:02.970 --> 00:31:04.390
I didn't know."

00:31:04.390 --> 00:31:07.740
Then I went through how do you solve a problem?

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:10.120
The problem wasn't three million, the problem
was insurance.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:11.360
I said, "Wait a second.

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:12.990
What if we insured McDonald's?"

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:16.270
And they said, "Yeah."

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:20.350
So we insured McDonald's, so they wrote me
a check for three million.

00:31:20.350 --> 00:31:26.470
Then I went to the board and said, "Yeah,
we just launched this thing, and we haven't

00:31:26.470 --> 00:31:30.280
sold a single song yet, but we're $3 million
in profits."

00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:32.250
Tom Bilyeu: That's amazing.

00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:34.800
I wanted to punch myself in the mouth when
I read that story.

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:35.960
No, no, no, for real.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:38.740
This is one of those things that I really
want to know.

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:42.050
I want there to be a process that I can use.

00:31:42.050 --> 00:31:46.730
Like here are the three things you have to
ask yourself at any moment of failure or something.

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:48.080
That would be so useful.

00:31:48.080 --> 00:31:52.290
Because reading that, and this, I think, is
your superpower.

00:31:52.290 --> 00:31:55.990
It's unbelievable the way that ... Yes.

00:31:55.990 --> 00:31:59.710
It is how it felt to read it.

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:02.640
In the book, he's telling the story like it's
happening in real time.

00:32:02.640 --> 00:32:07.020
I'm going to be the hero in the company, and
then, oh shit, the night before, "No, sorry,

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:08.960
you own $3 million."

00:32:08.960 --> 00:32:11.810
That's where most people tap out, and they
have a story where they tell their friends

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:12.810
they did this whole thing.

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:14.540
"I lost my job because what am I going to
do?

00:32:14.540 --> 00:32:15.570
It's $3 million."

00:32:15.570 --> 00:32:20.220
Jay Samit: I hate ... The modern version of
the dog ate my homework is when an entrepreneur

00:32:20.220 --> 00:32:24.660
says, "The company was really going really
well, but we couldn't raise any more money."

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:27.810
No, that's like you failed at raising money.

00:32:27.810 --> 00:32:29.100
You don't know how to raise money.

00:32:29.100 --> 00:32:32.660
You didn't go to people that could raise you
money.

00:32:32.660 --> 00:32:33.800
You didn't tap everything.

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:35.230
You didn't try crowdfunding.

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:36.860
Don't say "Oh, well.

00:32:36.860 --> 00:32:38.110
We ran out of money."

00:32:38.110 --> 00:32:43.751
Tom Bilyeu: Do you immediately go to "I need
money, but I don't yet know where I'm going

00:32:43.751 --> 00:32:46.950
to get it, but I know that I have a problem,
somebody else shares the problem, and the

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:47.950
solution would help us both.

00:32:47.950 --> 00:32:48.950
I'll get them to pay for it."

00:32:48.950 --> 00:32:49.950
Is it that sort of simple?

00:32:49.950 --> 00:32:57.680
Jay Samit: The other example was when I wanted
to sell training to Ford Motor.

00:32:57.680 --> 00:32:59.410
I'm 20-something years old.

00:32:59.410 --> 00:33:03.620
To shorten the story, I had a solution would
save them a couple hundred million dollars.

00:33:03.620 --> 00:33:05.160
I know nothing about cars.

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:08.770
I know nothing about Detroit, Ford, the old
auto industry.

00:33:08.770 --> 00:33:13.240
I'm in California, and I'm in my 20s, and
it's a very conservative, old fashioned, big

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:15.610
manufacturing, dah dah dah.

00:33:15.610 --> 00:33:19.160
I'm trying to solve for how to connect the
dots.

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:21.540
So put yourself in the other person's perspective.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:27.740
I'm trying to think who does that executive
that I want to figure out who to meet, what's

00:33:27.740 --> 00:33:28.740
their day like?

00:33:28.740 --> 00:33:29.740
What motivates them?

00:33:29.740 --> 00:33:31.690
What would get them excited?

00:33:31.690 --> 00:33:34.410
What would they spend time on?

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:39.411
So I'm thinking this is Middle America, this
is corporate America, this is Americana, this

00:33:39.411 --> 00:33:45.370
is America, the old hot dog, Chevrolet, and
football type thing.

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:46.720
This is Ford football.

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:48.190
Well, I looked.

00:33:48.190 --> 00:33:54.850
There was a football coach from Michigan State,
famous coach, award-winning coach, who just

00:33:54.850 --> 00:33:55.850
retired.

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:58.730
Easy to find him, call him up.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.670
"You're my new head of sales."

00:34:01.670 --> 00:34:03.030
He knows nothing about technology.

00:34:03.030 --> 00:34:05.080
All we had to do was go and get the meeting.

00:34:05.080 --> 00:34:07.930
They'd talk about the football game of such
and such, when the guy did the thing with

00:34:07.930 --> 00:34:08.990
the thing and dah dah dah.

00:34:08.990 --> 00:34:10.040
"What's the kid here for?

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:11.040
Okay, here.

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:12.040
He's got some business."

00:34:12.040 --> 00:34:13.040
I kid you not.

00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:14.040
It's that easy.

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:18.230
LinkedIn was Reid's way of turning that into
data.

00:34:18.230 --> 00:34:22.070
Tom Bilyeu: [crosstalk 00:34:18]
Jay Samit: You know somebody that knows somebody.

00:34:22.070 --> 00:34:23.340
We're all connected.

00:34:23.340 --> 00:34:27.060
Tom Bilyeu: Why do you say he's a smartest
person you've ever met?

00:34:27.060 --> 00:34:29.750
Jay Samit: He's absolutely the smartest person.

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:37.210
If you look at this original business plan
for LinkedIn, there's 10 key pieces of data.

00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:40.500
Number of users for the first five years and
revenue for the first five years.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:44.840
If you overlay the actual, it looks like a
glove.

00:34:44.840 --> 00:34:50.070
He sees things in a way that's farther ahead
than everybody else.

00:34:50.070 --> 00:34:54.450
Reid Hoffman was one of the first people to
mention to me this Airbnb idea.

00:34:54.450 --> 00:34:55.450
Really?

00:34:55.450 --> 00:34:57.290
I'm going to let people stay at my house?

00:34:57.290 --> 00:34:58.290
I don't think so.

00:34:58.290 --> 00:34:59.290
I'm going to stay at their house?

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:00.290
I don't think so.

00:35:00.290 --> 00:35:02.830
Oh, I should've paused and said, "A, Reid's
smarter than me.

00:35:02.830 --> 00:35:04.990
And B, it's not about me.

00:35:04.990 --> 00:35:10.180
I'm not the demographic for every case."

00:35:10.180 --> 00:35:17.820
Reid has invested and started so many successful
things since PayPal, and LinkedIn, and Kiva,

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:23.610
and Zynga, and the first money into Facebook
and connecting the first investors.

00:35:23.610 --> 00:35:27.160
Just one of those type of people.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:30.870
Everyone should spend their time trying to
be around people that you feel are smarter

00:35:30.870 --> 00:35:31.870
than you.

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:33.970
That doesn't necessarily mean more educated.

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:41.360
I'm no longer in the young whippersnapper
generation, so I have to spend a lot of time

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:45.210
with millennials to understand the world from
their point of view because they have a huge

00:35:45.210 --> 00:35:46.210
advantage over me.

00:35:46.210 --> 00:35:48.790
Tom Bilyeu: Do you do that because you have
younger kids?

00:35:48.790 --> 00:35:49.790
Jay Samit: No.

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:51.320
Tom Bilyeu: Or is there a way to systemitize
that?

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:56.580
Jay Samit: That's one of the reasons that
I teach at universities, and volunteer at

00:35:56.580 --> 00:35:58.800
hackathons, and try to work.

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:02.140
Because we calcify as humans.

00:36:02.140 --> 00:36:06.770
What we do is we develop habits to free our
mind to do other things, so we don't have

00:36:06.770 --> 00:36:07.950
to think about everything.

00:36:07.950 --> 00:36:10.580
A great example is when one of my sons was
looking for an apartment.

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:12.030
We were driving around.

00:36:12.030 --> 00:36:15.000
"Ooh, write down that phone number.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:16.000
We'll call.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:17.000
That's a good building."

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:18.910
He takes his phone and goes like this.

00:36:18.910 --> 00:36:20.390
Wouldn't have occurred to me.

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:21.900
Yes, I have a phone.

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:23.330
Yes, I know it takes pictures.

00:36:23.330 --> 00:36:24.570
Yes, I take pictures.

00:36:24.570 --> 00:36:28.520
But I have a habit that says "Grab a piece
of paper."

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:34.360
If you can break past the habits, you'll find
that there are problems that young people

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:39.500
are looking for that app because they assume
somebody must've already solved this.

00:36:39.500 --> 00:36:43.500
When they don't find it, they then stop as
opposed to you may have been the first person

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:46.330
to think about solving traffic with an app.

00:36:46.330 --> 00:36:53.490
And when you have a new field, AI, 3D printing,
augmented reality.

00:36:53.490 --> 00:36:54.940
It's virgin turf.

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:57.090
You don't have to be the best.

00:36:57.090 --> 00:37:02.870
Here's the takeaway: Be the best at what you
do or the only one doing it.

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:07.120
Because if you're the only one doing it, you're
the best.

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:08.360
That's a lot better than competing.

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:12.590
Tom Bilyeu: What are some classic mistakes
that you think entrepreneurs make?

00:37:12.590 --> 00:37:17.680
Jay Samit: Not delegating is the first one.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:18.680
Tom Bilyeu: Really?

00:37:18.680 --> 00:37:22.030
Jay Samit: The biggest problem people have
is the second person you hire is not going

00:37:22.030 --> 00:37:24.800
to be as good as you are at whatever it was.

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:31.360
So what I try to explain to first time entrepreneurs
is you're an A student at whatever that is,

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:32.990
you're going to have to hire C students.

00:37:32.990 --> 00:37:37.920
An A student gets a 90 on a test, a C student
gets a 60, but two of them get 120.

00:37:37.920 --> 00:37:40.150
Tom Bilyeu: That's a great point.

00:37:40.150 --> 00:37:44.360
Jay Samit: So three of them are outdoing you
guaranteed, and you have to then figure out

00:37:44.360 --> 00:37:46.370
the systems.

00:37:46.370 --> 00:37:51.860
The second one is, and I was guilty of this
for at least a decade if not longer.

00:37:51.860 --> 00:37:57.460
I would leave meetings so frustrated when,
to the older generation, "Why don't they get

00:37:57.460 --> 00:37:58.460
it?

00:37:58.460 --> 00:37:59.460
I am right.

00:37:59.460 --> 00:38:00.560
I am so right.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:01.560
What don't they see?"

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:04.940
I had this meeting at a major corporation
with the CEO that I got into, and I'm walking

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:11.000
down the long hallway in ARMA New York past
IBM's Electrics and IBM's Electrics, typewriters

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:15.980
on all the desks, realizing nobody in the
C suite was on PCs.

00:38:15.980 --> 00:38:19.180
I'm going like, "Ooh, this meeting's not going
to go well.

00:38:19.180 --> 00:38:23.660
Because I'm living in a digital age, and they're
in hieroglyphics."

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:27.210
What I realized was their job isn't to get
it.

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:29.030
